Upstairs to the right.

03:33.166 --> 03:36.100
Sweetheart, let me get in there
and check a pulse. Okay?

03:36.202 --> 03:37.702
When did you find him?

03:39.038 --> 03:40.237
Okay, he took a breath.

03:40.340 --> 03:42.406
Go ahead and get the Ambu bag out.

03:42.508 --> 03:44.809
Okay, drag
him out in the hallway.

03:44.911 --> 03:45.943
Okay.

03:47.847 --> 03:49.280
Is he a known addict?

03:51.718 --> 03:54.552
Okay. Can you get some Narcan?

03:54.654 --> 03:56.721
I can get him nasally real quick.

04:07.233 --> 04:10.067
Mickey? Hey, Buddy!

04:11.871 --> 04:13.838
He's coming back.

04:13.940 --> 04:15.039
Mickey?

04:21.680 --> 04:24.582
We've had this gentleman multiple
times in the last couple weeks.

04:24.684 --> 04:27.985
He'll probably wake up en route
to the hospital completely.

04:28.087 --> 04:32.156
But it's very common
that we have repeat overdoses.

04:35.561 --> 04:37.828
Heroin is definitively
back in America.

04:37.930 --> 04:39.830
<i>Over the last decade,
the number of addicts</i>

04:39.932 --> 04:41.465
<i>nationwide has more than doubled,</i>

04:41.567 --> 04:43.367
<i>and the overdose rate
is four to five times</i>

04:43.469 --> 04:44.902
<i>what it was in the 1970s,</i>

04:45.004 --> 04:47.271
<i>which was basically
the heroin decade.</i>

04:47.373 --> 04:49.273
The epicenter
of this new wave of junkie-dom

04:49.375 --> 04:51.942
is not the urban centers
of New York or Baltimore.

04:52.045 --> 04:53.878
<i>It's in the hills of West Virginia,</i>

04:53.980 --> 04:55.980
<i>smack in the middle of Appalachia.</i>

04:56.082 --> 05:00.384
We are a microcosm of everything that
has happened across the country,

05:00.486 --> 05:02.787
but it's just so focused right here.

05:02.889 --> 05:05.322
We knew that we had
to step up our efforts

05:05.425 --> 05:07.058
from a law enforcement standpoint.

05:07.160 --> 05:09.326
What we're trying to do
is clean things up

05:09.429 --> 05:12.830
to get back to the glory
that we once knew.

05:12.932 --> 05:14.165
Morton:
<i>Right now, at least</i>

05:14.267 --> 05:15.966
<i>according to what
statistics are available,</i>

05:16.069 --> 05:18.169
<i>Huntington is the worst hit
city in the state.</i>

05:18.271 --> 05:19.904
<i>In order to fight the problem,
the mayor here</i>

05:20.006 --> 05:21.872
<i>has assembled an office
of drug control policy.</i>

05:21.974 --> 05:25.743
Essentially modeling it after
the country's drug czar,

05:25.845 --> 05:30.014
which is, you know, kind of a crazy thing
for a town of 50,000 people to need,

05:30.116 --> 05:33.551
<i>but in light of the fact they're
averaging three overdoses a day,</i>

05:33.653 --> 05:37.354
I guess you sort of have to find a way
to fight crazy with some form of crazy.

05:38.424 --> 05:40.558
<i>One of this town drug czar's
best resources</i>

05:40.660 --> 05:44.161
<i>is Scott Lemley, a young "Moneyball"
sort of kid from the police department,</i>

05:44.263 --> 05:46.764
<i>trying to use statistics
to get a grasp on the problem.</i>

05:46.866 --> 05:49.066
How do the numbers
here work? Like, what's...

05:49.168 --> 05:52.002
Basically, all the overdose
deaths we've had in the county,

05:52.105 --> 05:53.838
they've all been opiate related.

05:53.940 --> 05:56.040
<i>If you look at
the city of Huntington,</i>

05:56.142 --> 05:57.842
<i>we have a death rate,</i>

05:57.944 --> 05:59.777
<i>119 per 100,000.</i>

05:59.879 --> 06:01.946
<i>National average is 13.</i>

06:02.048 --> 06:05.516
So we're about 11 times
the national average.

06:05.618 --> 06:10.087
Do you have figures about the socioeconomic
background of the people who are dying?

06:10.189 --> 06:12.890
We've had overdoses in the best
neighborhoods in Huntington.

06:12.992 --> 06:15.292
<i>We've had overdoses in the worst.</i>

06:15.394 --> 06:19.063
<i>It's across the board, it really is.</i>

06:19.165 --> 06:20.631
Morton:
<i>Jan Rader, a trained nurse</i>

06:20.733 --> 06:22.733
<i>and deputy chief of the
Huntington fire department,</i>

06:22.835 --> 06:24.395
<i>as well as the woman
who we just watched</i>

06:24.437 --> 06:25.870
<i>save an overdose victim,</i>

06:25.972 --> 06:27.972
<i>is also part of the drug task force.</i>

06:28.074 --> 06:30.674
It's sad when you can
drive around the city

06:30.776 --> 06:35.913
and you remember places
by who overdosed and died.

06:37.583 --> 06:41.552
Unfortunately, with this epidemic,
you have to throw out, you know,

06:41.654 --> 06:43.521
what you thought addiction was,

06:43.623 --> 06:45.523
what you thought an addict was.

06:50.062 --> 06:55.266
You know, I don't think the medical
field realized what they were creating

06:55.368 --> 06:57.468
<i>when this wonderful pain medicine,</i>

06:57.570 --> 06:59.370
synthetic opiates, was invented.

06:59.472 --> 07:02.940
Morton: <i>What's crazy is, all this
new smack and pill addiction</i>

07:03.042 --> 07:07.845
<i>can essentially be traced to one specific
opiate and its maker: OxyContin,</i>

07:07.947 --> 07:12.049
<i>released to the public by
Purdue Pharmaceuticals in 1996.</i>

07:12.151 --> 07:14.952
OxyContin is extended
release oxycodone.

07:15.054 --> 07:17.688
That's a very good drug
to prescribe to someone

07:17.790 --> 07:21.192
<i>with cancer pain, at the end of life.</i>

07:21.294 --> 07:23.194
Morton: <i>Dr. Andrew Kolodny
has been studying</i>

07:23.296 --> 07:25.763
<i>the skyrocketing rates of heroin
addiction across the country</i>

07:25.865 --> 07:27.898
<i>from its beginning
in prescription pills.</i>

07:28.000 --> 07:29.567
The way you get a blockbuster drug

07:29.669 --> 07:33.871
is by getting doctors to prescribe
it for things like low back pain.

07:33.973 --> 07:37.274
<i>And if it's a drug that is
very difficult to stop taking,</i>

07:37.376 --> 07:39.243
then you've got the magic formula.

07:39.345 --> 07:41.745
Morton: <i>Purdue campaigned
heavily throughout the '90s</i>

07:41.847 --> 07:43.814
<i>to convince doctors
that not only was OxyContin</i>

07:43.916 --> 07:45.683
<i>safe to prescribe for chronic pain,</i>

07:45.785 --> 07:47.218
<i>but that opiates in general,</i>

07:47.320 --> 07:48.919
<i>the drug class
that includes OxyContin,</i>

07:49.021 --> 07:51.522
<i>as well as morphine, Dilaudid,
and heroin,</i>

07:51.624 --> 07:53.123
<i>were far less addictive</i>

07:53.226 --> 07:55.359
<i>than all previous medical
science had shown.</i>

07:55.461 --> 07:59.163
Now, in fact, the rate of addiction

07:59.265 --> 08:02.166
amongst pain patients
who are treated by doctors

08:02.268 --> 08:03.834
is much less than one percent.

08:03.936 --> 08:06.470
The statistic that was
used over and over again

08:06.572 --> 08:08.872
was much less than one percent
of patients would get addicted.

08:08.975 --> 08:12.543
<i>But what you would find is
that what everybody was citing</i>

08:12.645 --> 08:14.979
<i>wasn't actually a journal article.</i>

08:15.081 --> 08:18.015
<i>It was a one-paragraph
letter to the editor.</i>

08:18.117 --> 08:20.417
And yet, that's what
was used as evidence

08:20.519 --> 08:24.622
and cited hundreds of times
by experts in the field

08:24.724 --> 08:26.690
as proof that we shouldn't be worried

08:26.792 --> 08:28.525
about getting our patients addicted.

08:28.628 --> 08:30.394
<i>Something you have to understand</i>

08:30.496 --> 08:32.996
<i>is that when when we talk
about opioid pain medicine,</i>

08:33.099 --> 08:37.101
<i>we're essentially
talking about heroin pills.</i>

08:37.203 --> 08:40.638
From the beginning of
the opioid addiction epidemic,

08:40.740 --> 08:43.006
the young people
who were opioid-addicted

08:43.109 --> 08:46.176
who were having trouble getting
enough pills from doctors,

08:46.279 --> 08:47.845
would go to the black market,

08:47.947 --> 08:49.627
and if they were in
a region of the country

08:49.715 --> 08:51.982
where heroin was available,
they switched.

08:54.320 --> 08:57.054
Morton: Can I ask you
how you started using?

09:02.995 --> 09:05.663
Had you ever touched
heroin before that or...?

09:05.765 --> 09:07.064
Why'd you switch?

09:08.934 --> 09:10.167
Ah.

09:29.055 --> 09:31.588
Morton: <i>What's particularly
insidious about opiate addiction</i>

09:31.691 --> 09:33.824
<i>is how quickly the body
develops a tolerance,</i>

09:33.926 --> 09:37.494
<i>requiring increasing amounts of the
drug just to generate the same effect,</i>

09:37.596 --> 09:40.831
<i>which, obviously, also increases
the chance of accidental overdose.</i>

09:40.933 --> 09:42.633
Morton: You're making
these big lines.

09:42.735 --> 09:46.270
If you had just started,
like, how big a...

09:46.372 --> 09:47.972
how big of a bump
are you doing? Okay.

10:06.625 --> 10:09.226
Morton: <i>While pill makers like
Purdue teed up all this madness,</i>

10:09.328 --> 10:11.829
<i>at the very least,
their product was regulated.</i>

10:11.931 --> 10:13.764
<i>If you took an 80mg OxyContin,</i>

10:13.866 --> 10:16.033
<i>you knew exactly how much oxy
you were taking.</i>

10:16.135 --> 10:17.334
<i>This is not the case with heroin,</i>

10:17.436 --> 10:19.169
<i>whose strength can vary
from batch to batch,</i>

10:19.271 --> 10:20.704
<i>and even bag to bag.</i>

10:20.806 --> 10:22.673
<i>On top of that, heroin has to be cut,</i>

10:22.775 --> 10:25.409
<i>because pure heroin alone would
kill even a veteran junkie.</i>

10:25.511 --> 10:28.312
<i>But what it's cut with
is anybody's guess.</i>

10:35.321 --> 10:36.353
Yeah.

10:41.660 --> 10:44.194
And how much could you
sell it for if you cut it?

10:50.035 --> 10:52.770
Are those... What are those?
Are those movie tickets?

10:52.872 --> 10:54.438
Oh, lottery tickets.

11:03.182 --> 11:04.815
So, what do you cut it with?
Is that...

11:06.952 --> 11:08.519
No. Okay.

11:12.124 --> 11:13.190
Mm-hmm.

11:14.827 --> 11:17.227
When you say pills,
do you use painkiller pills?

11:21.934 --> 11:24.535
Well, it's basically the same
thing as heroin, isn't it? Right.

11:24.637 --> 11:26.937
Morton: <i>The strongest cutting
agent of all is fentanyl,</i>

11:27.039 --> 11:29.773
<i>which is the strongest opioid
painkiller in existence,</i>

11:29.875 --> 11:32.643
<i>up to 50 times
the strength of pure heroin.</i>

11:33.679 --> 11:35.359
Do you know anybody
who cuts with fentanyl?

11:42.121 --> 11:43.187
Yeah?

11:50.396 --> 11:51.428
Really?

11:52.731 --> 11:54.898
They were intentionally trying
to get someone to overdose.

11:55.000 --> 11:56.033
Yes.
Okay.

11:56.135 --> 11:58.001
Morton: <i>Accidental
overdoses have long served</i>

11:58.103 --> 12:00.737
<i>as a perverse form of
advertising for heroin dealers.</i>

12:00.840 --> 12:03.774
<i>But the fact that they're using
pharmaceutical drugs to induce them</i>

12:03.876 --> 12:07.211
<i>shows just how extreme
the demand has grown.</i>

12:07.313 --> 12:10.614
<i>So now the heroin epidemic that
the OxyContin epidemic started,</i>

12:10.716 --> 12:14.117
<i>has itself turned into
a fentanyl epidemic.</i>

12:14.220 --> 12:16.487
They didn't understand why they're
cutting heroin with fentanyl,

12:16.589 --> 12:18.222
because fentanyl is really expensive.

12:18.324 --> 12:19.523
And I kind of have this idea

12:19.625 --> 12:21.091
that they're not cutting
heroin with fentanyl.

12:21.193 --> 12:22.793
They're cutting
the fentanyl with heroin.

12:22.895 --> 12:26.129
Morton: <i>With an increasingly
toxic, and seemingly inexhaustible</i>

12:26.232 --> 12:28.232
<i>supply of heroin
entering the country,</i>

12:28.334 --> 12:30.334
<i>the government has finally
started making overtures</i>

12:30.436 --> 12:33.670
<i>towards addressing the problem
on the demand side.</i>

12:33.772 --> 12:39.142
More Americans now die
every year from drug overdoses

12:39.245 --> 12:43.113
than they do from
motor vehicle crashes.

12:43.215 --> 12:45.255
Morton: <i>President Obama has
come to Charleston today</i>

12:45.351 --> 12:46.551
<i>to address the heroin problem.</i>

12:46.652 --> 12:48.252
But there's
an ironic note in the fact

12:48.354 --> 12:50.687
that this is a crisis
that started in 2007,

12:50.789 --> 12:52.356
before the Obama presidency,

12:52.458 --> 12:55.058
<i>and it's taken till the second-to-last
year of his administration</i>

12:55.160 --> 12:57.294
<i>to address a problem
that's been in plain sight</i>

12:57.396 --> 13:00.330
<i>down here for over eight years.</i>

13:00.432 --> 13:02.592
Obama: I've made this a
priority for my administration.

13:02.635 --> 13:04.835
With no other disease
do we expect people to wait

13:04.937 --> 13:06.670
until they're a danger to themselves

13:06.772 --> 13:08.906
to self-diagnose
and seek treatment.

13:09.008 --> 13:10.741
You understand that
here in West Virginia.

13:10.843 --> 13:14.945
We want to make sure the whole country
understands how urgent this problem is.

13:22.788 --> 13:25.889
One big part of the problem with
the opiate crisis in West Virginia

13:25.991 --> 13:29.560
is they've... this is basically
their first time dealing with it.

13:29.662 --> 13:32.062
<i>This is actually a big part
of a larger problem</i>

13:32.164 --> 13:34.565
<i>with America's response
to drug problems.</i>

13:34.667 --> 13:36.633
<i>It's just general inexperience
with addiction,</i>

13:36.735 --> 13:39.903
like what it means to be an addict,
why people behave the way they do

13:40.005 --> 13:43.941
<i>when they're hooked on heroin
or OxyContin or other opioids.</i>

13:45.511 --> 13:48.151
Mickey, the addict who overdosed at
the very beginning of our piece,

13:48.180 --> 13:49.680
he survived, thankfully,

13:49.782 --> 13:51.381
<i>and was lucky to find a bed</i>

13:51.483 --> 13:53.317
<i>at a treatment facility
here in Huntington.</i>

13:54.787 --> 13:56.620
What's up?
What's going on, bro?

13:58.591 --> 14:01.091
Morton: <i> Now, you've been here before,
though, right? You were telling me.</i>

14:01.193 --> 14:02.492
Mickey: <i>Yeah, the first
time I was in here,</i>

14:02.595 --> 14:04.995
I just wanted that
damn judge off my back.

14:05.097 --> 14:07.864
The second time I came in, I just...

14:07.967 --> 14:09.399
needed to learn how to manage,

14:09.501 --> 14:11.835
to get back to where I was
able to use and still work,

14:11.937 --> 14:13.303
and pay bills and all that shit.

14:13.405 --> 14:15.005
Yeah. And, yeah, it
don't work that way.

14:15.107 --> 14:17.474
That's like trying to be, like, a
social drinker for alcoholics.

14:17.576 --> 14:20.077
Yeah. I was trying...
Yeah, I failed miserably.

14:20.179 --> 14:21.545
That's when I met you guys.

14:22.881 --> 14:25.115
Morton: <i>How many times had
you overdosed before that?</i>

14:25.217 --> 14:26.283
Mickey:
<i>About seven.</i>

14:26.385 --> 14:27.818
<i>I mean, I've overdosed
a bunch more than that,</i>

14:27.920 --> 14:29.786
<i>but seven of them, I had
to go to the hospital for.</i>

14:29.888 --> 14:30.988
<i>Right. Okay.</i>

14:31.090 --> 14:32.823
I woke up with everything
from hoses down my throat,

14:32.925 --> 14:35.125
to adrenaline shots, to Narcan.

14:35.227 --> 14:38.128
All:
God, grant us the serenity

14:38.230 --> 14:40.797
to accept the things
we cannot change...

14:40.899 --> 14:43.400
Hell, I've lived on the
streets, riverbanks, and tents,

14:43.502 --> 14:44.901
spent winters out there.

14:45.004 --> 14:47.604
<i>I mean, it's... You would
think it'd be enough</i>

14:47.706 --> 14:50.474
<i>just to make a person
want to stop and change,</i>

14:50.576 --> 14:52.876
but, fuck, it didn't stop me.

14:54.580 --> 14:57.981
Most people come in here to get a
life that they've had prior to here.

14:58.083 --> 15:01.752
I never had one. It's like
learning to walk again.

15:01.854 --> 15:04.921
I mean, if this was easy,
everybody would do it and quit.

15:05.024 --> 15:07.424
Right. Right. Drug dealers
would be out of business.

15:08.627 --> 15:11.428
It ain't that easy.

15:11.530 --> 15:13.897
There are some alarming
new numbers out from the CDC

15:13.999 --> 15:17.034
showing a dramatic rise in the
heroin epidemic in this country.

15:17.136 --> 15:19.736
Anchorman: <i>Today the state of
Washington set a new record.</i>

15:19.838 --> 15:21.238
<i>For the fifth year in a row</i>

15:21.340 --> 15:23.073
<i>the number of heroin
overdoses went up.</i>

15:23.175 --> 15:25.876
Overdose deaths
skyrocketed in Ohio last year.

15:25.978 --> 15:28.412
Kolodny: <i>This is a problem
we're going to be dealing with</i>

15:28.514 --> 15:30.113
<i>for the rest of our lives.</i>

15:30.215 --> 15:33.316
What you're hearing is,
we cracked down on painkillers

15:33.419 --> 15:36.787
<i>and everybody
switched over to heroin.</i>

15:36.889 --> 15:39.723
There hasn't been
a crackdown on painkillers.

15:39.825 --> 15:44.728
There's still massive
over-prescribing of opioids.

15:44.830 --> 15:47.931
<i>Every state in the country
has within it counties</i>

15:48.033 --> 15:51.968
<i>that are feeling
the effects of this epidemic.</i>

15:52.071 --> 15:57.307
This is the worst drug addiction
epidemic in United States history.

