they'll kind of write their name,

16:40.586 --> 16:44.654
and put in a time frame of how
many years they spent out here.

16:44.757 --> 16:46.990
We're at about
60 to 80 feet below ground.

16:48.460 --> 16:49.893
So this is the first blast door,

16:49.995 --> 16:52.763
to protect measures of, you know,
before you get the capsule,

16:52.865 --> 16:56.032
who also has another blast door, too.

16:56.135 --> 16:57.501
And the purpose of this is...

16:57.603 --> 16:59.970
Pretty much to sustain the
equipment down here so nothing...

17:00.072 --> 17:01.371
In the case of a nuclear attack?

17:01.473 --> 17:02.706
Exactly. Exactly.

17:07.412 --> 17:10.480
Larsen: <i> This command capsule can
launch a nuclear missile strike</i>

17:10.582 --> 17:12.782
<i>against any target on the planet.</i>

17:12.885 --> 17:17.220
<i>The officers here pull 24-hour
shifts called "alerts."</i>

17:17.321 --> 17:19.823
<i>During that period,
they're responsible for ten</i>

17:19.925 --> 17:24.828
<i>of the 450 intercontinental
ballistic missiles, or ICBMs,</i>

17:24.930 --> 17:28.899
<i>buried at three bases
around the American West.</i>

17:29.001 --> 17:31.701
So we're having a little party
down here in the capsule today?

17:31.804 --> 17:32.969
Uh, it seems like.

17:33.071 --> 17:35.005
It's my 100 alert,

17:35.107 --> 17:39.876
so Lieutenant Busbee surprised
me with a cookie cake.

17:39.978 --> 17:42.879
Larsen: <i>One hundred
alerts means 2,400 hours</i>

17:42.981 --> 17:45.882
<i>locked in a bunker
no bigger than a family van,</i>

17:45.984 --> 17:47.884
<i>which may seem like a long time,</i>

17:47.986 --> 17:51.121
<i>but there have been officers
on continuous alert in here</i>

17:51.223 --> 17:53.256
<i>since 1963.</i>

17:53.358 --> 17:55.759
It might be super old,

17:55.861 --> 17:57.994
but it's still reliable

17:58.096 --> 18:00.730
and it still gets the mission done.

18:00.833 --> 18:02.866
Do you guys ever have
the feeling like,

18:02.968 --> 18:04.734
"Hey, we practice these things
all the time,

18:04.837 --> 18:06.970
"but we never actually use them"?

18:07.072 --> 18:08.505
We use these every day.

18:08.607 --> 18:10.473
The mission is deterrence.

18:10.576 --> 18:14.878
And part of deterrence
is being capable of doing it.

18:14.980 --> 18:19.416
So if the president
wants to actually launch,

18:19.518 --> 18:20.951
we are ready to go.

18:23.989 --> 18:25.722
Push door open.

18:25.824 --> 18:29.459
Three, two, one, mark.

18:29.561 --> 18:31.962
Larsen: <i>Many people thought
that when the Cold War ended,</i>

18:32.064 --> 18:34.231
<i>these weapons would go away too,</i>

18:34.333 --> 18:35.765
<i>but they never did.</i>

18:35.868 --> 18:39.469
<i>And the Air Force tests them regularly
at a secure base in California</i>

18:39.571 --> 18:42.072
<i>to show the world
that they still work.</i>

18:42.174 --> 18:43.773
<i>At a launch in late February,</i>

18:43.876 --> 18:47.110
<i>Pentagon leadership was
on hand to make sure.</i>

18:47.212 --> 18:49.112
Even though these
systems are getting old,

18:49.214 --> 18:53.416
anyone who is a nuclear power is
sure to be watching these tests

18:53.518 --> 18:55.819
and has to be at least aware

18:55.921 --> 18:59.756
that the United States nuclear deterrent
is as strong as it has ever been.

18:59.858 --> 19:02.926
Larsen: <i> The next morning, we sat
down with Deputy Secretary Work</i>

19:03.028 --> 19:05.028
<i>to ask him why he thinks
it's still important</i>

19:05.130 --> 19:06.897
<i>to have nuclear weapons at all.</i>

19:06.999 --> 19:09.232
The president, your boss, has said

19:09.334 --> 19:11.735
he'd like to see a world
without nuclear weapons.

19:11.837 --> 19:14.504
How does that play into the
current modernization program?

19:14.606 --> 19:19.342
Well, what the president says, in addition
to wanting to get rid of nuclear weapons,

19:19.444 --> 19:21.711
he says as long as we have them,

19:21.813 --> 19:24.681
they are going to be
safe, secure, and effective.

19:24.783 --> 19:27.851
So he recognizes very clearly,

19:27.953 --> 19:31.221
that as long as adversaries or
potential rivals or countries

19:31.323 --> 19:33.189
have nuclear weapons,
we're going to have them too.

19:33.292 --> 19:35.859
So as long as that is
our national policy,

19:35.961 --> 19:37.460
we will recapitalize them.

19:37.562 --> 19:41.464
Larsen: <i> The United States still
controls a massive nuclear arsenal</i>

19:41.566 --> 19:43.967
<i>powerful enough to end
the world as we know it.</i>

19:44.069 --> 19:46.836
<i>It's made up of what's called
the nuclear triad:</i>

19:46.939 --> 19:48.805
<i>Land-based ICBMS,</i>

19:48.907 --> 19:50.573
<i>gravity bombs and cruise missiles</i>

19:50.676 --> 19:52.275
<i>dropped from
long-range bombers,</i>

19:52.377 --> 19:54.177
<i>and missiles launched from submarines</i>

19:54.279 --> 19:55.845
<i>that hide in the ocean.</i>

19:55.948 --> 19:57.714
<i>Now, the military wants to spend</i>

19:57.816 --> 19:59.482
<i>as much as a trillion dollars</i>

19:59.584 --> 20:01.551
<i>to modernize all of it.</i>

20:01.653 --> 20:03.586
<i>And that's ignited an intense debate</i>

20:03.689 --> 20:06.056
<i>about whether we should
be spending so much</i>

20:06.158 --> 20:08.591
<i>on weapons we'll likely never use.</i>

20:08.694 --> 20:10.894
We spend more money
on nuclear weapons

20:10.996 --> 20:13.563
than all other countries combined.

20:13.665 --> 20:15.966
This is the epitome of overkill.

20:16.068 --> 20:18.201
Let's start the year
by putting to rest the notion

20:18.303 --> 20:20.704
that our nuclear deterrent
is unaffordable.

20:20.806 --> 20:22.539
That's just ridiculous.

20:22.641 --> 20:25.008
Larsen: <i>At the top of the
Pentagon's wish list</i>

20:25.110 --> 20:27.911
<i>is a new fleet of
nuclear-armed submarines.</i>

20:28.013 --> 20:33.383
<i>We traveled to an undisclosed location
off the southern coast to see why.</i>

20:34.953 --> 20:36.152
Larsen:
It's a pretty surreal feeling

20:36.254 --> 20:37.821
to be in the middle of the ocean

20:37.923 --> 20:40.924
and to come up on
a ballistic missile submarine.

20:41.026 --> 20:42.726
It looks like a giant steel whale.

20:42.828 --> 20:44.894
<i>This is the USS</i> Wyoming.

20:44.997 --> 20:47.831
<i>Beneath these hatches are
underwater launch missiles</i>

20:47.933 --> 20:51.167
<i>that together carry seven
times the total firepower</i>

20:51.269 --> 20:54.170
<i>unleashed during World War II.</i>

20:54.272 --> 20:57.841
Cue the launch of the 1C dive, dive.
Two blasts to dive alarm. Dive, dive.

20:57.943 --> 21:02.979
Dive! Dive!

21:03.081 --> 21:05.382
Establish launch conditions.
This is the captain.

21:05.484 --> 21:06.916
This is an exercise.

21:07.019 --> 21:08.818
Boat is XO, target package ID.

21:08.920 --> 21:11.354
Whiskey, Yankee, Oscar
has been directed.

21:11.456 --> 21:15.158
Larsen: <i> The crew simulates launching a
nuclear strike several times a day.</i>

21:15.260 --> 21:17.894
Obtain the launch key. Obtain
the launch key. Aye, sir.

21:17.996 --> 21:21.164
Why do you drill this component
of the mission so often?

21:21.266 --> 21:24.601
The nation as a whole is depending
on us to be able to deliver

21:24.703 --> 21:26.636
<i>whenever the president tasks us.</i>

21:26.738 --> 21:30.140
Any time of day, any time of night.
We cannot fail.

21:30.242 --> 21:32.075
Fourteen, aweigh.

21:32.177 --> 21:34.511
Fourteen, aweigh.

21:34.613 --> 21:37.180
Larsen: <i> That urgency is one of
the Navy's major justifications</i>

21:37.282 --> 21:40.283
<i>for replacing these submarines
with new ones.</i>

21:40.385 --> 21:45.822
<i>The core function here is to keep these 24
missile tubes up and running at all times.</i>

21:45.924 --> 21:47.490
<i>But the equipment that runs them,</i>

21:47.592 --> 21:49.025
<i>and much of the rest of the ship</i>

21:49.127 --> 21:52.028
<i>is getting too old to be reliable.</i>

21:52.130 --> 21:54.130
This is like 1970s technology.

21:54.232 --> 21:58.735
The size of it, which you see in an
old movie, you know, in a warehouse.

21:58.837 --> 22:02.605
So the upgrade for the Ohio
replacement will take this room

22:02.707 --> 22:07.544
and could probably put it into
basically a laptop-size computer.

22:07.646 --> 22:10.780
And then the hardware
that's made to run this

22:10.882 --> 22:13.550
is so out of date that it costs
the government more money

22:13.652 --> 22:15.952
to have someone actually
go back in and build that,

22:16.054 --> 22:17.921
and to be able to repair
some of that stuff, so...

22:18.023 --> 22:19.789
Space is very vital on a submarine,

22:19.891 --> 22:23.493
so every single big cabinet that we have
is taking away space from the crew.

22:25.764 --> 22:28.631
This is a nine-man bunk room. Okay.

22:28.733 --> 22:29.699
Right here next to the missiles?

22:29.801 --> 22:32.001
Next to the missiles.
We sleep with them.

22:33.672 --> 22:36.639
What's it like to sleep
between missile tubes?

22:36.741 --> 22:38.741
It feels kind of odd sleeping,

22:38.844 --> 22:40.710
you know, on a weapon
of mass destruction,

22:40.812 --> 22:42.879
but, you know,
you get used to it, I guess.

22:42.981 --> 22:44.314
It comes with the job.

22:44.416 --> 22:46.716
Larsen: <i>If the Navy gets its way
and we do buy new submarines,</i>

22:46.818 --> 22:51.488
<i>the first one is projected to cost
at least 8.8 billion dollars.</i>

22:51.590 --> 22:56.025
<i>And the eleven subsequent ships would cost
more than five billion dollars apiece.</i>

22:56.128 --> 23:00.296
<i>And that's just one part of the
nuclear modernization shopping spree.</i>

23:00.398 --> 23:02.899
The Air Force released more
details about its plans

23:03.001 --> 23:04.868
for a new long-range
strike bomber.

23:04.970 --> 23:07.070
Larsen: <i>A brand-new
fleet of B-21 bombers,</i>

23:07.172 --> 23:09.339
<i>to replace the B-2
and other models,</i>

23:09.441 --> 23:12.609
<i>could cost more
than 100 billion dollars.</i>

23:12.711 --> 23:15.578
<i>Stephen Schwartz is
a nuclear weapons analyst</i>

23:15.680 --> 23:19.048
<i>who says all this spending
is getting out of control.</i>

23:19.151 --> 23:21.684
We're actually spending more today

23:21.786 --> 23:24.020
to maintain and sustain

23:24.122 --> 23:25.955
and modernize our nuclear arsenal

23:26.057 --> 23:29.159
than we spent on average
during the Cold War

23:29.261 --> 23:31.327
when we were building
new nuclear weapons

23:31.429 --> 23:33.363
and testing them on a regular basis.

23:33.465 --> 23:34.831
That's just incredible.

23:34.933 --> 23:36.733
Do you ever step outside
your job and be like,

23:36.835 --> 23:42.405
"This is crazy. We've built the
world's most expensive, elite,

23:42.507 --> 23:45.808
practice football team that
we hope never plays a game"?

23:45.911 --> 23:48.411
Right. Well, the people
on the other side will say,

23:48.513 --> 23:50.580
"We use nuclear weapons every
day." I'm sure you've heard that.

23:50.682 --> 23:52.482
You know, the other
argument they'll say is,

23:52.584 --> 23:54.584
"Well, obviously,
all this stuff worked.

23:54.686 --> 23:56.586
"Okay, we spent trillions of dollars.

23:56.688 --> 23:58.788
We built all these weapons.
We're still here."

23:58.890 --> 24:02.659
That's a myth. That's probably the
number one myth of the Cold War.

24:02.761 --> 24:04.294
We could've done it with a lot less.

24:04.396 --> 24:06.196
How much? I don't know.
But we didn't need it all.

24:06.298 --> 24:07.697
We definitely didn't need it all.

24:07.799 --> 24:10.033
Larsen: <i>But even though
our arsenal was huge,</i>

24:10.135 --> 24:11.701
<i>it followed a certain logic.</i>

24:11.803 --> 24:14.070
<i>The weapons were
so big and so destructive</i>

24:14.172 --> 24:18.908
<i>that both sides knew
they would never be used.</i>

24:19.010 --> 24:21.678
<i>But now that we're modernizing,
we're building a new weapon</i>

24:21.780 --> 24:23.746
<i>that's moving us
in the opposite direction.</i>

24:26.184 --> 24:28.451
<i>At the National Security
Campus in Kansas City,</i>

24:28.553 --> 24:32.188
<i>technicians are working on
a polarizing new project.</i>

24:32.290 --> 24:34.591
Behind me is a trainer model

24:34.693 --> 24:37.360
of the B61-12 gravity bomb.

24:37.462 --> 24:41.064
This weapon itself has
become very controversial

24:41.166 --> 24:45.868
because of its ability to target
more accurately and to be smaller.

24:45.971 --> 24:48.871
<i>The explosive yield
of the B61-12</i>

24:48.974 --> 24:52.242
<i>can be throttled down
to .3 kilotons,</i>

24:52.344 --> 24:54.244
<i>a thousand times less powerful</i>

24:54.346 --> 24:56.813
<i>than the warhead
on our current ICBMs.</i>

24:56.915 --> 24:58.915
<i>And a new tailfin allows it</i>

24:59.017 --> 25:00.850
<i>to be guided directly to its target,</i>

25:00.952 --> 25:04.220
<i>giving it accuracy that our
nuclear bombs have never had.</i>

25:04.322 --> 25:06.289
<i>Taken together, those traits could</i>

25:06.391 --> 25:08.258
<i>make these weapons more usable</i>

25:08.360 --> 25:10.093
<i>in the minds of American commanders.</i>

25:10.195 --> 25:13.863
<i>Dr. William Perry was in
charge of America's nukes</i>

25:13.965 --> 25:16.599
<i>as our 19th Secretary of Defense.</i>

25:16.701 --> 25:19.702
It's hard to argue
there's anything wrong

25:19.804 --> 25:22.538
with having lower yields
or more accuracies.

25:22.641 --> 25:23.706
But in fact, there is.

25:23.808 --> 25:25.608
We can devise tactical situations

25:25.710 --> 25:27.377
in which we might want to use it.

25:27.479 --> 25:31.547
The problem is,
those tactical situations

25:31.650 --> 25:33.349
are a snare and a delusion

25:33.451 --> 25:35.885
<i>because they lead us into believing</i>

25:35.987 --> 25:38.721
<i>we can use nuclear weapons
at lower levels of danger</i>

25:38.823 --> 25:42.358
<i>that would not lead to a full-scale
attack on the United States,</i>

25:42.460 --> 25:45.194
that would not lead
to a full-scale nuclear war.

25:45.297 --> 25:47.797
That's a very,
very dangerous assumption.

25:47.899 --> 25:51.734
Larsen: <i>At the age of 88,
Perry's now the leading voice</i>

25:51.836 --> 25:55.138
<i>warning that we're in increasing
danger of a nuclear disaster.</i>

25:55.240 --> 25:56.673
The threat is real.

25:56.775 --> 26:00.143
In a sense, we are living
on borrowed time.

26:00.245 --> 26:03.579
Larsen: <i>Which is all the more
striking because during the Cold War,</i>

26:03.682 --> 26:06.983
<i>he helped build up our nuclear
force to what it is today.</i>

26:07.085 --> 26:09.652
I've devoted a lot of my career
helping to build this deterrence

26:09.754 --> 26:11.421
because I believed it was important.

26:11.523 --> 26:13.289
Even as I did that,

26:13.391 --> 26:15.558
I understood that it was
a dangerous situation,

26:15.660 --> 26:18.428
that we should be looking
for some way out of the trap.

26:18.530 --> 26:20.063
I did not see any way out of it

26:20.165 --> 26:22.432
when there was a Soviet Union
that was hostile.

26:22.534 --> 26:25.535
But when the Cold War ended,
that opened up the possibility

26:25.637 --> 26:27.203
of moving away from deterrence.

26:27.305 --> 26:29.739
And we did start moving away
for the first few years,

26:29.841 --> 26:32.475
but now we're falling back
into the deterrence trap.

26:32.577 --> 26:36.713
Are we in danger of a new
nuclear escalation though?

26:36.815 --> 26:39.682
Yes, we are, already, in a sense,

26:39.784 --> 26:41.818
<i>restarting the nuclear arms race.</i>

26:41.920 --> 26:43.486
<i>Even more dangerously,</i>

26:43.588 --> 26:45.922
we're on the threshold
of starting a new Cold War.

26:46.024 --> 26:48.825
Larsen: <i>That's because
the more we modernize,</i>

26:48.927 --> 26:53.029
<i>the harder it is to convince countries
like China, North Korea, or Russia</i>

26:53.131 --> 26:55.798
<i>not to ratchet up
their own nuclear programs.</i>

26:55.900 --> 26:57.467
Anchorman:
<i>A key question tonight:</i>

26:57.569 --> 27:01.204
<i>How will Russia respond to
America's enhanced nuclear bombs?</i>

27:08.380 --> 27:12.215
Larsen: <i> When President Obama hosted a nuclear
security summit in March of this year,</i>

27:12.317 --> 27:15.885
<i>Russia refused to attend.</i>

27:15.987 --> 27:19.489
<i>At the same time, Russia is building
new submarines and missiles,</i>

27:19.591 --> 27:22.959
<i>and they're warning that they
may be forced to use them.</i>

27:32.537 --> 27:36.339
The Russians have used terms
about nuclear weapons

27:36.441 --> 27:38.741
that we view
as extremely destabilizing.

27:38.843 --> 27:41.878
This is stuff we haven't heard
since the Cold War, literally.

27:41.980 --> 27:43.513
And the Russians have said,

27:43.615 --> 27:46.382
"Look, we'll go
to nuclear weapons early.

27:46.484 --> 27:48.851
We will escalate
to deescalate."

27:48.953 --> 27:52.288
<i>Once you start up the escalatory
ladder with a nuclear weapon,</i>

27:52.390 --> 27:55.057
<i>you don't know where
you're going to end up.</i>

27:56.361 --> 27:58.728
Are we living in
dangerous nuclear times?

27:58.830 --> 28:01.063
I believe...

28:01.166 --> 28:04.233
that the likelihood
of a nuclear catastrophe today

28:04.335 --> 28:06.636
is greater than it was
during the Cold War.

28:06.738 --> 28:10.173
And our public is
blissfully unaware of that.

28:10.275 --> 28:13.543
Is there any way out of this?

28:13.645 --> 28:15.711
Maybe not, but I hope so.

28:15.814 --> 28:17.680
The first thing we have to do
is don't make it worse.

28:17.782 --> 28:21.083
If we go ahead with the complete
remodernization of the force today,

28:21.186 --> 28:23.619
we're just digging the hole deeper.

28:23.721 --> 28:25.888
Sooner or later,
we've got to get out of it.

28:25.990 --> 28:27.757
It's not going to be soon,

28:27.859 --> 28:29.579
but we ought to be moving
in that direction,

28:29.627 --> 28:31.561
not in the wrong direction.

